e author’s explorations of its farthest and most noteworthy reaches, treating readers to an intimate environmental tour of a shad camp near the George Washington Bridge, the Arthur Kill (home of the resurgent heron colonies), the Hackensack Meadowlands, the darkness under a giant Manhattan pier, and the famously polluted Gowanus Canal. A new epilogue details some of the remarkable changes that have come upon New York Harbor in recent years. Waldman’s prognosis is a good one: Ultimately, environmental awareness and action has allowed the harbor to begin cleaning itself. Although it will never regain its native biological glory, the return of oysters, herons, and a host of other creatures is an indication of New York Harbor’s rebirth.This excellent, engaging introduction to the ecological issues surrounding New York Harbor will appeal to students and general readers alike. Heartbeats in the Muck is a must-read for anyone who likes probing the wilds, whether country or city, and natural history books such as Beautiful Swimmers and Mannahatta.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEstuarine biology -- New York Harbor (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEstuarine biologyzNew York Harbor (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEstuarine ecology -- New York Harbor (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEstuarine ecologyzNew York Harbor (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNew York Harbor (N.Y. and N.J.). 4aEnvironment. 4aNew York City & Regional. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  abiodiversity.  acity.  aclean water act.  aecology.  aenvironment.  aestuary.  amarine.  anature.  aoyster.  aurban.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823249879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823249879/original  